    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The strongest philosophical argument is that government regulation inevitably creates a \"chilling effect,\" where the fear of state punishment causes citizens to self-censor before speaking, thereby destroying the very free speech the law claims to protect. This aligns with the First Amendment's core principle that the government must remain entirely passive in the marketplace of ideas, acting only as a neutral referee rather than an active censor. Furthermore, the \"slippery slope\" of regulatory power means that once the state gains the authority to define what constitutes \"harmful\" speech, it will inevitably expand that power to suppress dissenting views it dislikes, effectively turning the internet into a state-controlled propaganda tool. Ultimately, true free speech requires absolute immunity from state interference, as any attempt to regulate content is inherently an act of censorship.",
